    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>St Louis</placeName>
                <date>November 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1849</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Knowing the interest you take<lb/> in the welfare of your
                coreligionists, throughout the<lb/> Union, I therefore avail myself of the
                opportunity<lb/> afforded me of communicating with you.</p>
            <p>The congregation to which I belong and to which<lb/> I have the honor of being
                Secretary has increased so<lb/> rapidly within the last twelve months (so much<lb/>
                beyond our most sanguine expectations) that I<lb/> am sure you will participate with
                us in our<lb/> exultations. At our last Holy Days our<lb/> synagogue was crowded to
                almost suffocation<lb/> not less than from Five to Six hundred persons<lb/> being
                present. When but a few years ago<lb/> we could but boast of fifty or sixty and it
                is<lb/> still increasing. We have been more than<lb/> fortunate in securing the
                valuable services of<lb/> the <persName>Revd. Nathan Davidson</persName>, a
                gentleman qualified<lb/> in an eminent degree for the offices he now<lb/> fills,
                which is rather more than ordinary,<lb/> arduous, being Shocet as well as
                Hasan,<lb/> having myself been a constant attender both<lb/> to the
                    <placeName>London</placeName> and <placeName>New York</placeName> synagogues
                I<lb/> consider myself justified in saying that he<lb/> cannot be surpassed in his
                style of Reading</p>
            <p rend="The following is written in pencil at the top right corner of the page.">W :
                Agent: <persName role="author">Henry Meyers</persName>
                <date>1849</date>?</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>his <sic>pronounciatin</sic> being most perfect and his<lb/> singing clear from those
                additions so often made<lb/> use of. You may think my Dear Sir that I have<lb/> over
                drawn my picture, but I am sure had you<lb/> been present, and seen the satisfaction
                depicted<lb/> upon the countenances of his hearer as thy life<add>?</add><lb/> the
                House of Prayer, after hearing the Revd gentleman<lb/> you would agree with me, that
                I have fell<lb/> far short in my c<add>?</add>. There is also a<lb/> new German
                Synagogue started which in a<lb/> little time will become of importance, we
                have<lb/> also two Benefit docu<add>?</add> both flourishing,<lb/> and we are about
                organising a <sic>Benevelent</sic><lb/> Society for the Relief of our less
                fortunate<lb/> Bretheren, the progress of which I will inform<lb/> you of at some
                future day in the mean<lb/> time Dear Sir Believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">to be your most obdt. Servant</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Henry Meyers</persName> Secretary</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <hi rend="underline">United Hebrew Congregation</hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName>
                    <sic>Myers</sic>
                </persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
